TL; DR

To answer the question “How to become a data analyst” is kind of tricky for beginner. It somehow requires a bit of analytical thinking to hit the ball. In short, the question and the answer itself forms a recursive situation. If we answer this question the old way, we might trapped ourselves into a embarrasing dilemma. It is best if we could answer the question with the mindset of a data analyst.

The earliest writing on statistics was found in a 9th-century book entitled Manuscript on Deciphering Cryptographic Messages.

Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#History

Wilhelm Schickard designed and constructed the first working mechanical calculator in 1623.

Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science#History

IMHO: we could become a data analyst via

  • Learning from different resources
  • Doing data projects
  • Sharing what we’ve learned
  • Hunting for a relevant job, ITERATIVELY

Another IMHO: skillsets of a data analyst

  • Command line / Markup languages
  • Spreadsheet
  • SQL / Python / R
  • Applied statistics
  • Applied machine learning

Answer Like a Data Analyst

What’s wrong with IMHO?

IMHO is actually the opposite of “Data Driven” decision making

Data Analyst is all about being “Data Driven”

Data Analyst makes decisions interpreted from data, not one’s instincts or experience.

So how do we answer this question like a Data Analyst?

First thing first: problem decomposition

  • The definition
  • The how

What is a Data Analyst, anyway?

https://www.quora.com/What-is-a-data-analyst-1

Source: https://twitter.com/cdixon/status/428914681911070720

Source: https://twitter.com/josh_wills/status/198093512149958656

Source: http://drewconway.com/zia/2013/3/26/the-data-science-venn-diagram

Source: https://r4ds.had.co.nz/explore-intro.html

After quick surveys, we might come out a brief definition

A data analyst is someone who uses programming/software handling data-relevant tasks including importing, cleaning, exploration, modeling and communication in aid of making a data-driven decision.

Then comes the “HOW” part

Well, this probably simplified too much…

\(\text{Statistics} \cap \text{Computer Science} \cap \text{Applications} = \text{Data Science}\)

Source: https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b018ttws

Start job hunting after 2/3 of your preparation
